This paper is about image super-resolution using deep convolutional networks, which is a topic related to computer vision (cs.CV). The paper proposes a deep learning method for single image super-resolution, which involves training a deep convolutional neural network (CNN) to map low-resolution images to high-resolution ones. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper involves exploring different network structures and parameter settings to achieve trade-offs between performance and speed, which suggests that it may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) and neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-categories.
